Name: ISS 401: Fire and Emergency Response Service
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with a fire department that is on call 24/7 for the installation) Supports all Incident Command System requirements for emergency response to safely mitigate structural, aircraft, hazardous materials, CBRNE, technical rescue, wild land, natural/manmade disasters and other miscellaneous incidents. This program provides 24 hour/365 day capability for the Installations Emergency Control Center (ECC) or 911 Dispatch Services under the Directorate of Emergency Services (DES). Supports all program compliance requirements to include emergency response to safely mitigate aircraft incidents (Rotary or Fixed Wing).

Name: ISS 111: Internal Review
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with the tools necessary to conduct and manage necessary audits).  Conduct audits of a critical nature to the command with short response times. This includes the review of audit readiness documents before they are uploaded into the Army Audit Depository. Work should be documented using audit standards including work paper preparation, reports and recommendations.  Conducts audits that provide an independent, objective assessment to the command. This includes audit readiness sustainment audits.  Manage audits, surveys, and reviews performed by external agencies as required by law, directed by regulation or by the Commander.

Name: ISS 106: Religious Support
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with a chaplain and staff to conduct various religious services on the installation). Advise the Commander and staff on matters of religion, morals and morale.  This program provides complete worship experiences comparable to the civilian community, integrated within the military community to meet the needs of the authorized population for the free exercise of religion.  This program provides for comprehensive, lifelong religious education/faith formation programs and processes that complement worship experiences, include all ages, respond to diverse life situations, and facilitate the spiritual resilience of the Army community. This includes weekday, as well as weekend, activities.

Name: ISS 408: Snow, Ice, and Sand Removal
Description: (i.e. Provides the snow and ice removal services on the installation) Clear snow, sleet, ice and sand from primary roads, and sidewalks parking lots for critical building access, and ports. This program provides for the clearing of snow, sleet, ice, and sand from airfields pavements. This program provides for the clearing of snow, sleet, ice, and sand from railroads. Provides for the clearing of snow, sleet, ice, and sand from secondary paved surfaces (Secondary Roads, Service Roads, Parking Lots and other Sidewalks).

Name: ISS 254: Business Operations
Description: (i.e. Provides all the restaurant, bowling alley, golf courses, and other forms of entertainment services on post). Ensures Soldiers and Families have an opportunity to participate in bowling programs and centers offering open and league bowling and services such as bowling instruction, retail, food and beverage, and other market-driven recreational activities as facility allows. Clubs, Food, Beverage and Entertainment (CFBE) Operations may include theme operations, catering, snack bars, dining, beverage, social events, entertainment, and other services normally associated with a restaurant and entertainment center, as well as hospitality support for official events. Provide programs and activities for the workforce including athletics and sports, tours, tickets, support for cultural events and organizational days, rod and gun activities, fitness facilities, libraries, social events, entertainment and installation wide events as well as official hosting and representation.

Name: ISS 104: Client Services
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with legal advise and services associated with taxes and wills). Multi-faceted program: Provides legal assistance to active duty military members through the Soldier readiness processing (SRP); mobilizing and demobilizing personnel in accordance with 10 USC 1044A and AR 27-3; assisting Soldiers with actions involving administrative due process; and assisting and advising on their personal legal affairs. Assists and advises Family members with actions involving their personal legal affairs Assists and advises retirees with actions involving their personal legal affairs. Assists and advises eligible civilians with actions involving administrative actions/proceedings.

Name: ISS 505: Compliance Services
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the personnel and tools to ensure environmental compliance on the installation) Provides for timely and accurate review and analysis of installation projects and activities (e.g., training and testing) for potential impacts related to environmental laws, regulations and Final Governing Standards (FGS) or Host Nation-equivalent mandates. Allows the customer to accomplish the mission by successfully acquiring and maintaining appropriate permits or Host Nation/FGS equivalent as defined by HQDA's Environmental Policies and Guidance. Provides management and disposal services for hazardous waste and other waste that requires special handling, as defined by Federal/State regulations, Host Nation/FGS equivalent or HQDAs Environmental policy and guidance.

Name: ISS 402: Custodial Services
Description: (i.e. Provides custodial services for infrastructure on the installation). This program provides basic cleaning to installation facilities IAW the Enterprise Municipal Custodial Services Performance Standards in the Performance Work Statement to include Child Care Centers and Fitness Centers.

Name: ISS 504: Other Utility Services
Description: (i.e. Provides funding for the operation and maintenance of the gas/propane infrastructure on the installation) Provides upgrades to facilities and equipment to improve energy efficiency via alternative financing methods, i.e., Energy Savings Performance Contracts (ESPC) and Utility Energy Services Contracts (UESC). Provides natural gas/propane for heating, domestic hot water, cooking, power generation, and other miscellaneous uses via a Utilities Privatization contract. Includes all utilities privatization contract costs to operate, maintain, repair and recapitalize the plants and distribution systems.

Name: ISS 906: Battle Command Training Center (MTC)
Description: Provides integrated collective mission command staff training and exercises for home station, mission planning and rehearsal, and pre-deployment training ranging from platoon to Combined Joint Task Forces (CJTF) levels. Provides individual operator and leader mission command sustainment training and new personnel training in a Live Virtual Constructive-Gaming (LVC-G) integrated training environment IAW programs of instruction. Provides mobile training teams, exercise support, network solutions, and distributed training to support Spokes and deployed or remote sites IAW Mission Command Training Strategy Implementation Plan, Hub and Spoke strategy and Home Station Master Plan.

Name: ISS 300: Clothing and Equipment
Description: Manage the Central Issue Facility (CIF) to include receive, store, issue, process Organizational Clothing & Individual Equipment (OCIE).

Name: ISS 405: Master Planning
Description: (i.e. Provide the Garrison CDR and staff with the personnel and expertise to conduct master planning for all facets of the installation). Establish a vision and future direction for safely and efficiently managing, acquiring, or reducing real property at Army installations in order to support the current mission, transformation and management process IAW AR 420-1. Establish a framework of installation management to review allocation of limited resources that affect, or are affected by, the use of real property assets. This service includes planning, programming and execution functions of MLCON iaw AR 420-1, Army Facilities Management, DA PAM 420-1-2, Army Military Construction and Non-Appropriated Funded Construction Development and Execution, UFC 2-100-01, Installation Master Planning and other applicable regulations. This service includes analyzing capabilities to support mobilization, deployment, and stationing actions.

Name: ISS 510: Pest Management
Description: (i.e. Provides the funding for services related to pest control within the infrastructure on the installation). Prepares an integrated pest management plan (IPMP) that defines pest management requirements, responsibilities, and resources needed to correct pest problems at each installation. Provides visits of facilities as required to inspect, identify and eliminate the presence of existing or potential public health and wood destroying and nuisance pest problems. Provides response and completion of service orders to evaluate and correct pest problems that are a threat to mission, health, safety, and to prevent property damage.

Name: ISS 904: Range Operations
Description: (i.e. Provides for the operations and maintenance of the ranges on the installation). Provides for range, training facility/area, and targetry maintenance to plan, manage, and operate safe and efficient sustainable range complex use. Ensures the safe conduct of military, civilian personnel, contractors and other agencies involved and/or affected by training operations. Provides scheduling of range complex facilities. Provides subject matter expertise to support and facilitate the design, analysis and fabrication and/or reconfiguration of range facilities to meet an immediate requirement.

Name: ISS 305: Food Services
Description: Provide Dining Facility meal service. Operates the Subsistence Supply Management Office & Food Program Office.

Name: ISS 303: Military Clothing and Sales
Description: Provides the military clothing and sales venues located on the installation.

Name: ISS 102: Administration and Civil Law
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with legal advise and services associated with administrative and civil law). Provide advise in all areas of admin and civil law to commanders in daily operation. Provide full legal support including advice and representation to commanders and staff, Civilian Personnel Advisory Centers, in Labor and Employment matters. Provide full legal support to commanders in Environmental Law in accordance with Federal and state law and regulations. Provide full legal support to commanders in all facets of contracts and fiscal law in accordance with Federal law and Army regulations.

Name: ISS 304: Laundry and Dry-Cleaning Services
Description: Provides laundry service and dry cleaning service on the installation.

Name: ISS 604: Emergency Management
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the personnel and tools to plan and implement early warning to all personnel on the installation in the event of an emergency) Provides for the development of deliberate & incident planning to prepare for, prevent, mitigate the potential effects of, respond to & recover from emergencies resulting from all hazards (natural, technological, terrorism, CBRNE) in order to enhance EM capability. The EM program plan addresses identified threats/vulnerabilities to the Installation. Includes public awareness campaigns, Mass Warning System planning and sustainment and preparation for specific high risk weather seasons utilizing FSEs, FEs, and TTXs with supporting ARS and Ips.

Name: ISS 803: Continuing Education Services
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with tuition assistance, GT improvement and education counseling). Provide education/career counseling services to include customer assistance and interviews to determine appropriate education goals/plans/services programs and to serve as a gateway for effective/efficient provision of individual services. Provide education counseling services to facilitate off duty self-development programs at the post-secondary levels (vocational/technical/undergraduate/graduate). Provide tuition assistance to assist Soldiers pursuing and completing post-secondary education goals, not to exceed a Master's degree.. Includes standardized tests that determine eligibility for specialized training and support the Army's personnel retention rate, selection, and classification process including language proficiency testing.

Name: ISS 253: Sports, Recreation, and Libraries
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with Fitness Centers, Library services, and Aquatic Centers on post). Provides Garrison capabilities to conduct functional fitness programs in support of TC 3-20.21, required to assist commanders in meeting the physical requirements of the Mission Essential Task List (METL). The Library and Information Services Program consists of libraries that support readiness, the military mission, quality of life, voluntary education, professional and technical education and training, lifelong learning, transition and career assistance, and leisure needs of military communities. Aquatic Facilities are a key component of mission readiness. Aquatic Training Programs are required for unit water survival training, enhancing Soldier swimming skills, support rehabilitation of wounded warriors and support the general health of the military community.

Name: ISS 112: Installation Safety and Occupational Health
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the tools necessary to manage an on-post safety program).  Develop, justify, manage, plan, organize, and implement a Garrison safety program to manage compliance with statutory and regulatory standards.  Identify accident casual factors and potentially unsafe practices or conditions, and recommendations for corrective actions to prevent mishap recurrence and reduce hazardous conditions. The function includes: mishap screening, accident feeder reports, notifications, investigation, report reviews/coordination, report processing, mishap log, board appointments, command level reviews, counter measure development, malfunction recording for components, OSHA recordkeeping.

Name: ISS 201: Family Housing Management
Description: (i.e. Provides the management and oversight of privatized housing on the installation). This program implements policies for eligibility, assignment, occupancy and termination of government owned and leased family housing. This SSP provides for management and oversight of the Housing Services Office (HSO). Provides for the oversight of privatized housing services. This programs plans and executes the AFH furnishings & equipment program.

Name: ISS 400: Facilities Engineering Services Mgmt
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with the tools needed to conduct long-term planning for all the services provided by the Director of Public Works (DPW) on the installation) The Annual Work Plan (AWP) is a systematic approach that provides a framework that captures the upcoming year of execution for the Director of Public Works UP DA PAM 420-6. The AWP, as a one year slice of an installation's six year plan, must work towards achieving the installation's long term vision (strategic Goals).  This program captures all engineer functional requirements needed to provision garrison services and maintain quality facilities. Provides work management and execution using good work management practices to control and accomplish in-house or contract RP maintenance mission.

Name: ISS 202: Army Lodging Management
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with Army lodging services to include reception, operations, maintenance and custodial). Provide accommodations to authorized travelers. Perform scheduled and unscheduled maintenance/repair services. Perform reservations, assignments, termination; and provide customer services. Provide common area cleaning, laundry, and supply services. Provide guest room cleaning. Perform scheduled and unscheduled maintenance/repair services. Perform reservations, assignments, termination, and provide customer services. Provide standard hotel amenities and guest services. Provide standard hotel amenities and guest services.

Name: ISS 903: Training Land Sustainment
Description: (i.e. Provides for the operations and maintenance of the training land on the installation). Provides the oversight and subject matter expertise necessary for the successful performance of needed land rehabilitation projects in support of Senior Commander training goals and objectives. Provides the capability to create, analyze, manage, and distribute authoritative standardized spatial information, products, and services for the execution of training strategies and missions on U.S. Army ranges and training lands.

Name: ISS 800: Military Personnel Services
Description: (i.e. Provides casualty assistance support; CAC/ID card services; services to transitioning service members). This program provide Military casualty services and liaison services for Family members between local funeral personnel and military burial personnel. This program provides those personnel services required by customers upon arrival/departure from an installation. This program provides those services required to deploy and redeploy Soldiers. This program provides CAC/ID Card services to customers as required by personnel actions initiated by customer. This program provides transition services for separating Soldiers. This program provides post-retirement services to customers in the geographical area. This program provides reassignment processing for Soldiers between installations  and distribution services between units and the installation.

Name: ISS 602: Anti-Terrorism Services
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the personnel and tools to plan and implement Anti-Terrorism planning and prevention on the installation). Provides the capability for the garrison commander to develop, implement and manage the installation AT Program; coordinate program requirements with installation organizational and tenant activities, local, state and federal agencies. Provides the garrison commander the capability to conduct required risk management to mitigate vulnerabilities or accept risk through comprehensive program reviews, vulnerability, criticality and risk assessments. It allows garrisons the ability to make decisions and apply resources to protect units, facilities and programs including DoD personnel, family members, civilians and contractors.

Name: ISS 250: Substance Abuse
Description: (i.e. Provides units with the ability to conduct urinalysis to test for illegal drug use). This program provides for the operation of a forensically secure Installation Drug Testing Collection Point. The program identifies and deters drug use and enhances individual readiness, and delivers Unit Prevention Leader (UPL) certification and recertification training, in accordance with applicable policy and regulations. This program is funded with OSD Fenced Funding. This program allows for the operation of a forensically secure Installation Drug Testing Collection Point. The program identifies and deters drug use and enhances individual readiness, in accordance with drug-free workplace and applicable regulations. This program plans, manages, directs and evaluates substance abuse education and training activities.

Name: ISS 900: Airfield Operations
Description: (i.e. Provides for the operations and maintenance of the installation airfield). Provide management/oversight to ensure a safe and efficient airfield environment to support aircraft operations. Support non-tactical airspace air traffic control (ATC) Services. Provide for the safe, orderly, and expeditious flow of arriving and departing air traffic. Maintain and certify non-tactical ATC equipment. Provide and maintain flight planning capabilities to include equipment, staff, airfield advisory services and access to air traffic related data for processing flight plans for local, national, and international air traffic systems.

Name: ISS 113: Administrative Management
Description: (i.e. Provides the installation with official mail service and provides units with printing services through the Document Automation and Production Service (DAPS)). Process incoming official mail and distribution for the installation in accordance with DODI 4525.8, DOD manual 4525.8-M and AR-25-51, 28 USC, 39 USC.  Provide Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) and Privacy Act (PA) support to authorized installation activities in accordance with 5 USC 552 & 552a, EO 13392, Federal Information Security Management Act (FIMSMA), and DOD and Army Regulations.  Process outgoing official mail and distribution for the installation in accordance with DODI 4525.8, DOD manual 4525.8 - M, and AR-25-51, 18 USC, 39 USC.  Provide personal mail services as specified by this SSP. Provide Army Records Information Management. System (ARIMS) services to authorized installation.

Name: ISS 603: Installation Security Program Mgmt Support
Description: (i.e. Provides the installation access control personnel the ability to vet and clear visitors before they enter the installation). Program facilitates unit readiness by ensuring that appropriate personnel have been vetted and cleared for accessions, employment, deployment, information systems access, facility access and other mission requirements. It includes processes and actions required for security clearances. Program facilitates unit readiness by ensuring that appropriate personnel have been vetted and cleared for accessions, employment, deployment, information systems access, facility access and other mission requirements. It includes processes and actions required for suitability/trustworthy determinations.

Name: ISS 507: Pollution Prevention Services
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the personnel and tools to prevent pollution and waste on the installation). Provides the customer(s) with the ability to meet the compliance requirements set forth in sections 301 through 313 of the Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act (EPCRA) and applicable Final Governing Standards (FGS). Provides the customer with data and analysis to apply source reduction or waste minimization in order to reduce releases, wastes, pollution, and costs from an installation’s current business practices, industrial processes, base operations, or other routine and recurring sources of wastes, pollution, or releases to the environment.

Name: ISS 506: Conservation Services
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the personnel to ensure compliance with endangered species on the installation) Provides for timely and accurate initial review and evaluation of installation projects and training/testing activities in accordance with cultural and natural resources laws, policy, guidance, and regulations, and Final Governing Standards (FGS) and host-nation equivalents. Provides required actions or tasks in accordance with natural resources laws and regulations, specific to the Endangered Species Act (ESA), FGS and host nation equivalents. Promotes environmental awareness and provides for increased stewardship and sustainability of cultural and natural resources

Name: ISS 700: Automation
Description: Provides for the administration and operation of the Office of the Director/Chief of Information Technology and for all installation operation automation activities, to include office automation.

Name: ISS 905: Training Support Center
Description: (i.e. Provides for the operations and maintenance of the training aids that are used for training on the installation). Provides for the loan, issue, receipt and store Training Aids Devices, Simulators and Simulations (TADSS) warehouse. Provides Instructors/Operators (I/Os) and Operators for DA specified virtual TADSS. Provides for the visual inspection, functional testing, diagnostic testing, check for general cleanliness, preventative maintenance, checks & services (PMCS), and preparation for reissue for TADSS. Provides familiarization training for those TADSS requiring familiarization and certification prior to issue from the warehouse that are non-virtual TADSS.

Name: ISS 901: Mobilization and Deployment Support
Description: The Installation Mobilization Support Plan implements a standardized approach to prepare for and execute critical support to mobilization operations in order to facilitate the readiness of reserve component Soldiers and formations transitioning to and from active duty. Plan and conduct mobilization exercises to ensure installation readiness to rapidly build and integrate mobilization support capabilities ICW the Supported Command, MEDCOM, ASC, ARNG AND USARC.

Name: ISS 414: Facilities Maintenance - Army Family Housing
Description: (i.e. Provides the minor repairs and waste removal that is not covered under privatized housing).  Provides maintenance and repair activities necessary to keep an inventory of real property in good working order. Executed through Demand Maintenance orders (DMO) which are used for required minor repairs after a system or component fails. This includes the abatement and disposal of Horizontal Structures hazardous Waste such as sewage spill clean ups, asbestos and PCB piping removal, and other waste disposal resulting from sustainment activities.

Name: ISS 121: Management Analysis
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with tools necessary to manage all stationing movements for units on and off the installation; as well as the installation Interactive Customer Evaluation (ICE) program). Provide overall integration, planning, monitoring, and coordination of BRAC actions, transformation initiatives, and/or AR 5-10 stationing actions. This includes both CONUS and OCONUS actions as well as inter- and intra-installation movements of units and organizations. Examples of actions supported include, but are limited to: Korea Transformation, Army 2020 directives/actions, Total Army Analysis (TAA) directives/actions, overseas installation closures or activations, etc. Provide Senior and Garrison Commanders with the tools and data necessary to effectively capture requirements and cost; and then monitor and report unit movements as necessary and directed.

Name: ISS 100: Installation Management
Description: (i.e. Garrison staff to assist with the management of all garrison related duties and functions) Manage and direct garrison day to day operations; formulate vision, goals, policies and objectives provide program direction to directors and special staff, manage garrison and base support services delivered to standard; manage garrison infrastructure to support Soldiers, Families, and Civilians, and deliver Family and garrison programs. Identify, develop and maintain mutually beneficial coalitions with local and tenant leaders, Garrison staff and the Installation community as delegated by the Senior Commander (SC).

Name: ISS 251: Army Community Service
Description: (i.e. Provides all the services you find at the installation ACS building). Support and enhance all Army Community Service programs by expanding their resource base through promotion and utilization of available tools and resources. Prevention and intervention programs and services for a wide range of support of individual life situations to include the range of Family Violence. Advocacy for and response to victims of domestic violence as well as prevention of domestic violence through education. Home Visiting Program providing services and parenting skills education to parents with a newborn or child, ages 0-3 or at-risk Families with young children, ages 0-3. Programs and support activities designed to assist leaders, Soldiers, their Families and Department of Army Civilians who deploy and their families to successfully manage the challenges of mobilization and deployments before, during, and after they are mobilized regardless of their geographical location.

Name: ISS 116: Support Agreement (MOU/MOA) Mgmt
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with tools necessary to author memorandums of understanding/agreements between the garrison and variety of customers). This program will negotiate, develop, and conclude a variety of high-emphasis agreements with Inter and Intra- agencies. This includes the reimbursable relationship required by DoD regulations. In coordination with the MACOM and/or Regional lead and legal advisor, this program will also negotiate, develop, and conclude agreements with a variety of customers. This includes a reimbursable relationship required by law. This program will conduct Triennial reviews of existing agreements, updating or terminating as necessary. This program provides oversight of mandatory Federal management controls programs.

Name: ISS 118: Installation TDA Management
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with tools necessary to manage their personnel and associated employees). This program provides manpower execution guidance/data analysis to the Garrison Commander, Garrison activities, and higher HQs. It also processes equipment requests for Garrison activities. This program provides analytical and advisory support to the Garrison Command Group. This program provides TDA Documentation/Command Plan input and processes equipment requests for Garrison activities. This program provides input to higher HQs to assist in the Identification and validation of civilian and military manpower requirements.

Name: ISS 411: Facilities Maintenance - Vertical
Description: (i.e. Provides minor vertical facility repairs to infrastructure on the installation) Provides maintenance and repair activities necessary to keep an inventory of real property in good working order. Executed through Demand Maintenance orders (DMO) which are used for required minor repairs after a system or component fails. This includes the abatement and disposal of building hazardous waste from sustainment activities.

Name: ISS 403: Refuse Removal
Description: (i.e. Provides trash and recycling services to tenants on the installation). Integrated Solid Waste Management (ISWM) is a comprehensive approach to managing non-hazardous solid waste that encompasses green procurement, waste prevention, recycling, and disposal programs. Manage non-hazardous solid waste, construction and demolition waste, landfills, in accordance with Federal, state, host nation and local laws with the intent of providing a safe clean environment managed under a cost efficient, integrated and progressive program.

Name: ISS 406: Real Estate/Real Property Administration
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR with the ability to account for all property on the installation) This program documents real property assets in compliance with CFO Act, DoDI 4165.14, 10 USC 2721, and other federal, state, and local, and laws. Provides status, cost, area, capacity, condition, use, and management of real property. This program researches, gathers, and analyzes real property information, prepares pertinent documents, and makes recommendations in response to statutory requirements. This program manages the process of granting termed use of Army property to other entities.

Name: ISS 404: Maintenance - Grounds
Description: (i.e. Provides the grounds improvement around the outside of infrastructure on the installation). This program provides improved grounds maintenance in the developed areas of the installation that requires intensive level of maintenance. This program provides semi improved maintenance in the areas of the installation used for operational and maintenance purposes. This program provides maintenance in the areas of the installation used for weapon ranges, road shoulders in undeveloped areas, grazing lands, lakes, ponds, and wetlands.

Name: ISS 500: Electrical Services
Description: (i.e. Provides funding for the operation and maintenance of the electrical/lighting infrastructure on the installation). Provides electricity for lighting, power, ventilation, heating, cooling, and building equipment using government-owned plants and distribution system components. Includes all in-house and contract (service contract and commercial activities contract) costs to operate the plants and distribution system components. Provides electricity for lighting, power, ventilation, heating and cooling, and building equipment via a Utilities Privatization contract.

Name: ISS 600: Physical Security
Description: (i.e. Provides the installation with access control at the installation gates which supports unit physical security). Provides administration and operation of access control points, visitor control center, and access control equipment. Access control is designed to restrict and/or control entrance to property and/or installations to only those authorized persons. Provides a mechanism to screen, identify and prevent access to personnel deemed a threat to the installation. Provides for maintaining required intrusion detection alarm systems, PS infrastructure, and electronic equipment, as required by regulation or risk analysis to protect personnel, HRP, MEVA, and HRT. Eliminates the need for posting 24/7 armed security personnel/soldiers at installation facilities containing AA&E, sensitive or classified material.

Name: ISS 420: Facilities Maintenance - Horizontal
Description: (i.e. Provides minor horizontal facility repairs to infrastructure on the installation) Provides maintenance and repair activities necessary to keep an inventory of real property in good working order. Executed through Demand Maintenance orders (DMO) which are used for required minor repairs after a system or component fails. This includes the abatement and disposal of building hazardous waste from sustainment activities.

Name: ISS 301: Retail Supply
Description: Retail Supply – operate the installation SSA;  request, receive, store, issue, ship materiel.

Name: ISS 701: Communication Systems and System Support
Description: Provides Army NIPR and SIPR email, enabling users to access their Army email from anywhere in DoD, and collaborate with any Army user worldwide via a Global Address List and enterprise calendar sharing.  Provides the AESD system which provides full lifecycle support for escalation and tracking of incidents and problems at the various Tier levels and situational awareness to IT service delivery issues and efficiencies.

Name: ISS 503: Waste Water Services
Description: (i.e. Provides funding for the operation and maintenance of the waste water facility infrastructure on the installation) Provides domestic and industrial waste water treatment services using Government-owned plants and collection systems. Includes all in-house and contract (service contract and commercial activities contract) costs to operate the plants and collection systems. Provides domestic and industrial waste water treatment services via a Utilities Privatization contract. Includes all utilities privatization contract costs to operate, maintain, repair and recapitalize the plants and collection systems.

Name: ISS 302: Asset Management
Description: Provides management and oversight of the installation's Logistic and Readiness Centers (LRCs) which support unit training (TRADOC only), MOB/DEMOB operations (Mobilization sites); coordinate reporting, metric tracking, equipment life cycle management requirements.   Coordinate Government Purchase Card (GPC) travel card services.  Provides management and oversight of LRC safety, personnel, environmental, security, and facilities.

Name: ISS 307: Transportation Services - NTVs
Description: Manages and provides non-tactical vehicles (NTVs) to include Life, Health, Security, and GSA fleets.  Provides transportation motor pool (TMP) operations; dispatch, service records, utilization monitoring.  Provides testing and licensing for government employee and service member operations for NTVS.  Provides the installation shuttle bus service.

Name: ISS 501: Heating/Cooling Services
Description: (i.e. Provides funding for the operation and maintenance of the heating/cooling infrastructure on the installation) Provides steam, hot water, and chilled water for heating, cooling, domestic hot water, and/or facility processes using government-owned central heating/cooling plants and distribution systems. Includes all in-house and contract (service contract and commercial activities contract) costs to operate the plants and distribution systems. Provides steam, hot water, and chilled water for heating, cooling, domestic hot water, and/or facility processes via a Utilities Privatization contract. Includes all utilities privatization contract costs to operate, maintain, repair and recapitalize the plants and distribution systems.

Name: ISS 109: Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO)
Description: (i.e. Provides commanders with EEO advice, training and support to help prevent discriminatory actions in the workplace). Process EEO Complaints of discrimination in accordance with AR 690-600 and other applicable directives and provide required reports.  EEO Program officials advise and provide appropriate assistance to managers/supervisors a bout the status of EEO program within each manager's area of responsibility.  Direct, monitor and implement employment related, career development actions for individuals with disabilities and provide required reports. Monitor and track reasonable accommodation requests.  This SSP requires that the Commander make early efforts to prevent discriminatory actions and eliminate barriers to equal employment opportunity in the workplace. This is accomplished by proactive measures such as training and education.

Name: ISS 200: UEPH/SEBQ/UOQ Management
Description: (i.e. Provides planning for the housing of unaccompanied enlisted personnel housing (UEPH)) This program implements policies for eligibility, assignment, and occupancy of UPH. This program provides input to planning, programming, budgeting and execution for Permanent Party barracks with regard to UPH. This program plans and executes the UH furnishings management program.

Name: ISS 703: Information Assurance
Description: Provides the processes and infrastructure required to ensure authentication, confidentiality, availability, data integrity, and non-repudiation of messages and information exchange on the network communication infrastructure.  Provides assured data, information and system integrity through the use of defense in depth processes and capabilities.  Provides all aspects of communication security (COMSEC) support to the installation.

Name: ISS 308: Transportation Services - Personal Property
Description: Provides personal property counseling; manages personal property shipments, storage and payment.  Provides privately owned vehicle storage for unit deployment; passport and visa application services; manages the oversight of the commercial travel office.

Name: ISS 105: Claims
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with an on-post service to conduct claims related to damages caused when personal property is damaged during a PCS).  A program to provide support to Soldiers and civilian employees who suffer loss and damage to their personal property incident to service, including loss or damage suffered during their household goods shipment, and non-shipment incident to service loss or damage, and also to support the DP3 Program.  A program to promptly investigate and adjudicate existing and potential tort claims against the Army and Department of Defense to identify and limit agency and United States Government liability and monetary damages as well as preserve evidence required for future litigation. A program to recover from tortfeasors and third party payers costs of medical care, lost military pay, and property damage caused by third parties.

Name: ISS 107: Public Affairs
Description: (i.e. Provides support to Commanders and Soldiers on all public affair related activity within the unit to include a variety of digital/audio/photo support) This business process leads to the development and execution of communication planning efforts and provides PA advice and policy support to the command, staff, and supported organizations /commands.  This business process provides, prepares for, manages and coordinates the online sharing and exchange of digital text, audio, photos and videos using internet and social media platforms to proactively provide information, receive feedback, and engage in effective interactive communication with a variety of internal and external audiences.

Name: ISS 502: Water Services
Description: (i.e. Provides funding for the operation and maintenance of the water facility infrastructure on the installation). Provides operation for potable and non-potable water uses for domestic and industrial purposes using Government-owned water systems including plants and distribution. Includes all in-house and contract (service contract and commercial activities contract) costs to operate the plants and distribution systems. Provides water for potable and non-potable uses for domestic and industrial purposes via a Utilities Privatization contract. Includes all utilities privatization contract costs to operate, maintain, repair and recapitalize the plants and distribution systems.

Name: ISS 252: Child, Youth, and School Services
Description: (i.e. Provide Soldiers with child care and youth programs on post). Support the All-Volunteer Force by reducing the conflict between mission and parental responsibilities regardless of duty station. Child Care an youth Program Spaces for eligible children 6 weeks to 18 years of age are provided through an integrated delivery system of facility based, home-based and outreach services delivered both on and off post. Program quality and quantity is ensured by meeting statutory requirements, DoD policy and Army standards, enforced by mandatory internal annual inspections ( DoD Certifications) and external validation (National Accreditation). The mission of the Army CYSS Youth Program is to support the resilience, well-being, readiness and retention of Army Families by reducing the conflict between military mission requirements.

Name: ISS 601: Law Enforcement Services
Description: (i.e. Provides the installation with law enforcement personnel to support rule of law and physical security). Provides for the maintenance of the safety and security of Army installations (and Joint Bases) and its members through police patrol and response operations. Provides for the resourcing and management of law enforcement emergency dispatch services. Provides for the ability to conduct specialized LE investigations of misdemeanor crimes and serious traffic accidents which occur on Army installations (and Joint Bases). Provides for the resourcing and management of maintaining installation police records and reports.

Name: ISS 702: Multimedia/Visual Information Processes
Description: (i.e. Provides units with local audio/video/photography/media equipment and services). Provide all types of Photography Services, Graphics Arts Services, and all types of Multimedia Services.  Provides Command Channel and closed circuit TV (CCTV) Services; provide local audio/video productions. Provide public address system / presentation support for official functions (set up, operations, and tear down). Provide various VI Media / Equipment Support Services.

Name: ISS 306: Material Support Maintenance
Description: Provide maintenance support for tactical materiel, night vision and optics, armament (fire control and weapons), power generation equipment, recovery equipment, communication equipment, fire suppression, battery and hydraulic equipment.

Name: ISS 115: Program Budget
Description: (i.e. Provides the Garrison CDR and staff with tools to program their annual budget).  This program is the statutory and regulatory defined management of appropriated funds. This program tracks and executes current/prior year annual funding and the reimbursable program. Mid-year review. This program provides liaison and assistance to Garrison Commander, staff, and external agencies. This program identifies budget requirements and anticipated funding for next year's annual funding.

Name: ISS 103: Criminal Law and Discipline
Description: (i.e. Provides Soldiers with legal advise and services associated with criminal law and UCMJ). A program to provide legal advice in accordance with law and regulations.  A program to provide legal advice in accordance with law and regulations.  Post Trial Processing, Quality Control Management & Systems. Technical advice/expertise, and oversight performed by a Legal Administrator, United States Army Warrant Officer.  Program manages and administers all facets of commander's military justice program IAW legal statutes and Army regulations.  A program of victim and witness assistance in compliance with legal statutes and Army regulations. A program to prosecute violations of Federal law committed on Army installations, or violations that involve Army interest or property.

Name: ISS 902: Command and Control
Description: Coordinate and synchronize daily operations across all USAG Directorates, Support Offices, tenants, partner organizations and off-post agencies (off-post agencies such as Federal, State, County, City entities as required). Develop and maintain weekly USAG Master Activities and Long Range training calendars. Plan and execute quality ceremonies and events. Ensure the installation maintains 24/7/365 day capability for situational awareness (SA) and Common Operating Picture (COP) of critical information and events, allowing the Senior Commander and the Garrison Cdr to make informed and timely decisions, and provides an expandable base of operations (Emergency Operations Center [EOC activation]) to execute the Anti- Terrorism/Force Protection and All Hazards Response Plan Contingency Operations (real world or exercise) and ARFORGEN.

Name: ISS 309: Supply and Storage
Description: Operates the installation SSA; request, receive, store, issue, ship materiel.  Manage bulk POL operations.  Asset management/property book - account for and assign  responsibility for installation property.  Provide core Ammunition Supply and Amnesty Service (operate the Ammunition Supply Point (ASP).
